Creative Writing Analysis Through Examination of the SCP Foundation¶

108 Final Project by Patrick DeKelly

Introduction¶

With creative AI models being in the zeitgeist now, there is a discussion about where creativity and inspiration come from. AI models are attempting, and somewhat successfully, to break down the creative process and emulate it. However, humans can arguably be said to approach creativity the same way. Humans break down sources of inspiration in our head and use those components to create something new. This begs the question: how much is a particular brush stroke or line of writing inspired by an individual piece of art weve seen in the past? While it would likely be impossible to ever know this to that point of precision perhaps we can still get some broader insights as to where creative inspiration comes from.

This project aims to analyze short story writing to find trends, similarities, and potential sources of inspiration. By breaking down human made writing using machine learning techniques, perhaps we can gain some insight into the creative process.

Description of the SCP foundation and motivation for its use¶

The SCP foundation (Website: https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/) is a wikipedia style database of short stories written in the SCP universe. This follows a fictitious secret organization that creates Special Containment Procedures (SCP) in an attempt to contain various anomalous entities and objects. They follow the format of faux classified documents describing the Special Containment Procedures (SCP) for these entities and objects. Broadly similar in concept to something like the X-files. While many articles are written in a scifi/horror genre, they are quite varied. Many are also humorous, fantastical, or existential.

While it does sound like an unusual dataset to perform writing analysis on, there are several aspects of it to make for a potentially unique opportunity:

  • The SCP universe is a completely crowdsourced collaborative independent universe with countless contributors. No one person created this and, by its very design, is not controlled by one single entity. For contrast, Marvel comics also has an extensive fictional universe with many writers but their content is all controlled by marvel.

  • It is very insular and writers are encouraged to build upon each other's work. In contrast, there may be lots of amateur fan fiction writers out there but they are all referencing outside works. The SCP articles largely just reference themselves and, as such, they are all contained within the database.

  • While there are many different writers and styles, there are standard formatting conventions that make parsing of information easier. The articles will typically start off with this standard formatting then deviate as it is used as a jumping off point to start a narrative.

  • Of substantial interest is that when one SCP article includes or references another it is standard practice to refer to it by its identification code (ex. SCP-123). This makes it particularly easy to parse out this information as few other places can you expect such consistent formatting in creative writing text. This could be leveraged for social network analysis.

Feature engineering and preprocessing of text¶

Authorship¶

Due to inconsistent formatting of articles, it is somewhat tricky to programmatically extract the authors who wrote each article. Some are listed at the end of the page but in slightly different ways. Many are anonymous and some have no author information at all from what was gathered by the web scraper. Can only programmatically extract the authors for about 2000 articles. However, this should be enough for analysis later.

In [5]:
# create a function to attempt to find article author's names
def find_author(x):
    try:
        y = x.split(' SCP')[1]
        start = y.index( "Author: " ) + len( "Author: " )
        end = y.index( '\nLicense:', start )
        return y[start:end]
    except:
        try:
            y = x.split(' SCP')[1]
            start = y.index( '" by ' ) + len( '" by ' )
            end = y.index( ', ', start )
            return y[start:end]   
        except:
            try:
                y = x.split('Cite this page as:')[1]
                start = y.index( '" by ' ) + len( '" by ' )
                end = y.index( ', ', start )
                return y[start:end]
            except:
                return "<UNKNOWN>"
# apply function    
scp_df["author"] = scp_df["text"].apply(find_author)

# check ammount found
found_authors = scp_df[scp_df["author"] != "<UNKNOWN>"].shape[0]
print(f"{found_authors} articles have found authors by the previous methods")

2151 articles have found authors by the previous methods

Remove non-article text¶

Again the formatting of articles is not consistent. As such, many articles have text not part of the article itself. This might be acknowledgments, author pages, moderator notes, etc. These need to be removed if the goal is to analyze similarities and differences in writing style.

Other SCP Referenced in Articles¶

Of interest to me is that when one SCP article includes or references another, it is standard practice to refer to it by its identification code (ex. SCP-123). This makes it particularly easy to parse out this information as few other places can you expect such consistent formatting in creative writing text. I believe this could be leveraged to attempt social network analysis on the texts later.

In [10]:
# finding other SCPs referenced in articles
def extract_SCP_references(x):
    text = str(x)[1:-1].split()
    
# set up to remove punctation but *not* hyphens as they are important    
remove = string.punctuation
remove = remove.replace("-", "") # don't remove hyphens
pattern = r"[{}]".format(remove) # create the pattern

text = [str(i)[1:-1].split() for i in scp_df['text']]
code_arr = scp_df['code'].values
ref_scp = []
for i,t in enumerate(text):
    l = set()
    for x in t:
        if x.startswith("SCP-") and x.startswith(code_arr[i]) == False:
            # remove non hyphen punctuation at this point
            n = re.sub(pattern, "", x)
            # split on hyphen and take the second
            n = n.split("-")[1]
            # removing non-numbers.
            n = ''.join(ch for ch in n if ch.isdigit())
            try:
                l.add(int(n))
            except:
                # if the previous steps don't result in a number the SCP string was either censored or not actually an object
                # pass in this case
                pass
    ref_scp.append(list(l))

# ref_scp = [set(ref_scp)]
# ref_scp = list(ref_scp)
# place in dataframe
scp_df["SCPs referenced"] = ref_scp
# and the count of references
scp_df["SCPs referenced length"] = [len(i) for i in ref_scp]
reference_length = scp_df.loc[scp_df["SCPs referenced length"] > 0].shape[0]
print(f"There are {reference_length} articles that reference at least 1 other SCP")
scp_df.head()

Object Class¶

Most SCPs have an object classification. This in universe represents how difficult the object is to contain. The vast majority are classified safe, euclid, or keter but there are a few rarer classifications and the occasional article that will make up its own. They are as follows:

  • Safe: SCPs that are very easy to contain or do not need many resources to contain.
  • Euclid: SCPs that require more resources to contain completely or where containment isn't always reliable.
  • Keter: SCPs that are very difficult to contain or haven't yet been contained.
  • Thaumiel: SCPs used by personnel in containing or counteracting other SCPs.
  • Neutralized: SCPs that have been destroyed or disabled by intentional or accidental means.
  • Apollyon: SCP that are impossible to contain and/or are expected to breach containment very often.
  • Archon: SCP's that can be contained but are not due to their positive anomalous effects on our planet's reality.

There is also an anomalous classification listed. However, it does not appear in tags and is too general a word to parse out. Recent SCP articles have attempted a newer more complex classification system. However, this data is scrapped from a few years ago and I would rightfully criticize the new system for being more complex than it needs to be.

Similarity Search¶

Local Sensitivity Hashing¶

The implementation of local sensitivity hashing in the homework ended up being much slower than Jaccard similarity and too slow to be of practical use on a data set this size. I modified this implementation from this tutorial to suit my needs. Jaccard similarity would take hours to complete, and LSH from the homework even slower. This takes about 5 minutes to make the LSH forest and then query all rows for all documents.

In [20]:
%%time

# code adapted from https://www.learndatasci.com/tutorials/building-recommendation-engine-locality-sensitive-hashing-lsh-python/

# Number of Permutations
permutations = 256

#Preprocess will split a string of text into individual tokens/shingles based on whitespace.
def preprocess(text):
    tokens = set(text.split())
    return tokens


# Create Minhash Forest for Queries
def get_forest(data, perms):
    
    minhash = []
    # since minihash index != item number after deleting entries, create array of item number values in order
    item_nums = data["item_#"].values
    
    for text in data['text_processed']:
        tokens = preprocess(text)
        m = MinHash(num_perm=perms)
        for s in tokens:
            m.update(s.encode('utf8'))
        minhash.append(m)
        
    forest = MinHashLSHForest(num_perm=perms, l=10)
    
    for i,m in enumerate(minhash):
        forest.add(item_nums[i],m)
        
    forest.index()
    
    return forest

forest = get_forest(scp_df, permutations)

CPU times: total: 1min 3s
Wall time: 1min 52s

For debugging and sanity checking results, I compared with SCP-909. SCP-909 (aka Mr.Forgetful) is part of the "misters" series written in the same style. As such, we should expect similar documents to that one to most/all have "Mr." or "Ms." in title.

In [21]:
# Evaluate Queries
def predict(text, database, perms, num_results, forest, i_num):
    
    tokens = preprocess(text)
    m = MinHash(num_perm=perms)
    for s in tokens:
        m.update(s.encode('utf8'))
#   num_results +1 to account for the same article being in the dataset
    item_array = np.array(forest.query(m, num_results+1))
    if len(item_array) == 0:
        return None # if your query is empty, return none
#   remove entry for same article index from similarity results
    item_array = np.delete(item_array, np.where(item_array == i_num))
    
    result = database[database['item_#'].isin(item_array)]['title'].values
    
    return result, item_array

# Test function on single document
# Number of Recommendations to return
num_recommendations = 10
# preprocessed text array
documents = scp_df['text_processed'].values
# SCP-909 is part of a "misters" series so similar documents should most/all be mr. or ms. in title
q_text = documents[908]

result, item_result = predict(q_text, scp_df, permutations, num_recommendations, forest, 909)

print(f"Top Recommendation(s) item number(s) is(are) \n {item_result}")

Jaccard Similarity¶

LSH is a fast way to perform similarity search though it is not the only way. However, the combinations required to compare similarities to all other documents using other methods is not feasible. However, my plan is to leverage the top 5 recommendations made for each row made by LSH as a subset to try more computationally expensive methods on. The idea being that any combination that did not make it within the top 5 by LSH will be unlikely to be similar therefore may be safely skipped.

Combinations of 2 for a dataset of 7000 is ~25 million. Which would take roughly 3 to 4 hours on a regular laptop to do. By calculating the jaccard similarity for only the top results from LSH this cuts it down to 35,000 combinations instead to search through. It should be roughly ~700 times faster to do that subset.

In [24]:
%%time

# combinations of 2 for a dataset of 7000 is ~25 million.
# by calculating the jaccard similarity for only the top results from LSH this cuts it down to 35,000 combinations instead
# so it should be roughly 700 times faster to do that subset

def jaccardSim(d1,d2):
    ## Your code goes below
    inter = d1.intersection(d2)
    u = d1.union(d2)
    try:
        r = len(inter)/len(u)
    except:
        # For identifying and debugging error articles
        print("division by 0 error")
        print(f"i={inter} u={u}")
        print(d1)
        print(d2)
        r = 0
    return r

# lists for storing results
pair_labels = []
pair_sims = []
pair1_in = []
pair2_in = []
pair1_titles = []
pair2_titles = []

empty_results = set()
perfect_results = set()
mean_JS_by_row = []

for i, row in scp_df.iterrows():
    i_num = row["item_#"]
    JS_total = 0
    for j in row["lsh recommendations"]:
        if f"({j},{i_num})" not in pair_labels:
            j_sim = jaccardSim(preprocess(row['text_processed']),preprocess(scp_df[scp_df["item_#"] == j]["text_processed"].values[0]))
            # append results
            pair_labels.append(f"({i_num},{j})")
            pair_sims.append(j_sim)
            pair1_in.append(i_num)
            pair2_in.append(j)
            pair1_titles.append(scp_df[scp_df["item_#"] == i_num]["title"].values[0])
            pair2_titles.append(scp_df[scp_df["item_#"] == j]["title"].values[0])
            JS_total += j_sim
            # For identifying and debugging error articles
            if j_sim == 0:
                empty_results.add(row["item_#"])
            if j_sim >= 1:
                perfect_results.add(row["item_#"])
    mean_JS_by_row.append(JS_total/len(row["lsh recommendations"]))


JS_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict({"pair":pair_labels,
                                "jaccard_sim":pair_sims,
                                "title1":pair1_titles,
                                "title2":pair2_titles,
                                "item_#1":pair1_in,
                                "item_#2":pair2_in,})
# getting the mean is useful to judge the quality of the LSH in subsetting top recommendations.
# raise permutations till improvement is insignificant.
JS_mean = JS_df["jaccard_sim"].mean()


print(f"**True similarity scores**")
print(f"JS for {JS_df.shape[0]} combinations calculated")
# mostly debug print statements
print(f"The mean JS for the dataframe is {JS_mean}")
print(f"{len(empty_results)} results have JS of 0 and are likely in error")
print(f"{len(perfect_results)} results have JS of 1 and are likely in error")
# display the top results
display(JS_df.sort_values("jaccard_sim",ascending=False)[:20])

The articles found to be most similar by jaccard similarity make sense. We can see a lot of the misters articles paired together which is the most obvious to determine and is expected. Examining some of the other top pairs: (4231,1730) are both very long articles that include a lot of dialogue between military tactical units. The similarities are likely picking up on the common words used in the short, straight to the point, military speech as well as related faux military operation language in the document sections. (5373,5292) were written by the same author and seem to use similar formatting.

Some of the other pairs are less immediately obvious. A lot of the ones marked as most similar pairs seem to have a lot of dialogue and maybe the type of dialogue is similar. Hard to say without reading all the articles in detail but, ideally, the similarity search should be able to pick up on more than can be gather from a casual skimming of the texts.

Note on anomaly detection from previous runs.¶

This method was effective in identifying a few anomalies in the data in previous runs.

  • Some similarity scores were a perfect 1.0, which corresponded to articles that were deleted, missing, or had technical errors. The 1.0 scores were for the boiler plate text that were in their place. Abnormally high similarity scores like >0.7 were usually the same but slight variations due to authors notes and such.

  • This also identified articles that had no text. Either due to the crawler not reading them correctly or that the article simply had none and was told in pictures or some other format.

Both types of articles were deleted from subsequent runs but it was this method that detected them.

Also:

  • Some articles with high similarity scores had discriptive notes on CSS improvements by some moderator with screen name Croquembouche. These notes varied from article to article but all ended with "...like this!". Parsed that text out as it was unrelated to the arcticle itself.

Search for the most quintessential articles¶

As before it is not feasible to perform jaccard similarity on all possible article combinations. Instead Ill take a subset of the most likely candidates based on the mean jaccard similarity scores from their top articles. From this subset of rows, I can get that jaccard similarity for that article and all other rows. Taking a new jaccard similarity mean should provide us with potentially the most quintessential SCP articles.

# We'll take the top 20 by mean JS for this attempt
candidate_df = scp_df.sort_values(by=["mean JS for top recommendations"], ascending=False)[:20]

empty_results = set()
perfect_results = set()
mean_JS_by_row = []
i_num_by_row = []
title_by_row = []

for i, row in candidate_df.iterrows():
    i_num = row["item_#"]
    JS_total = 0
    for j, row2 in scp_df.iterrows():
        i_num2 = row2["item_#"]
        if i_num != i_num2:
            j_sim = jaccardSim(preprocess(row['text_processed']),preprocess(row2['text_processed']))

            JS_total += j_sim
            # For identifying and debugging error articles
            if j_sim == 0:
                empty_results.add(f"{i_num},{i_num2}")
            if j_sim >= 1:
                perfect_results.add(f"{i_num},{i_num2}")
    mean_JS_by_row.append(JS_total/scp_df.shape[0])
    i_num_by_row.append(i_num)
    title_by_row.append(row["title"])

print("done")

JSQ_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict({"item_#":i_num_by_row,
                                "mean_jaccard_sim":mean_JS_by_row,
                                "title":title_by_row})
# getting the mean is useful to judge the quality of the LSH in subsetting top recommendations.
# raise permutations till improvement is insignificant.
JSQ_mean = JSQ_df["mean_jaccard_sim"].mean()


print(f"**True Mean similarity scores**")
# mostly debug print statements
print(f"The mean JS for the dataframe is {JSQ_mean}")
# this time, some article pairs legitimately have a jaccard of 0 since looking 
# at all rows will *occasionally* result in a rare no shared token situation.
print(f"{len(empty_results)} results have JS of 0 and are likely in error")
print(f"{len(perfect_results)} results have JS of 1 and are likely in error")

%%time

empty_results = 0
perfect_results = 0
mean_JS_by_author = []
JS_by_author_list = []
works_count = []
# to keep sims seperate for plotting later
JS_author_df = pd.DataFrame({"author":[],
        "sims": []})
df2 = pd.DataFrame({"author":["name"]*3,
        "sims": [45, 5, 2]})


for author in prolific_scp_authors:
    author_works = list(scp_df[scp_df["author"] == author]['text_processed'].values)
    works_count.append(len(author_works))
    JS_author = []
    for x1, x2 in itertools.combinations(author_works, 2):
        j_sim = jaccardSim(preprocess(x1),preprocess(x2))

        JS_author.append(j_sim)
        # For identifying and debugging error articles
        if j_sim == 0:
            empty_results += 1
        if j_sim >= 1:
            perfect_results += 1
            
    author_sims = pd.DataFrame({"author":[author]*len(JS_author),
        "sims": JS_author})
    JS_author_df = pd.concat([JS_author_df, author_sims])
    JS_by_author_list.append(JS_author)
    mean_JS_by_author.append(sum(JS_author)/len(JS_author))

print("done")

JSA_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict({"author":prolific_scp_authors,
                                 "works_count": works_count,
                                "mean_jaccard_sim":mean_JS_by_author,
                                "list_jaccard_sim":JS_by_author_list})
# getting the mean is useful to judge the quality of the LSH in subsetting top recommendations.
# raise permutations till improvement is insignificant.
JSA_mean = JSA_df["mean_jaccard_sim"].mean()


print(f"**Author similarity scores**")
# mostly debug print statements
print(f"The mean JS for the dataframe is {JSA_mean}")

# Too many authors to plot in one plot. Therefor, chunk them out

# by works

scp_authors_least_works = list(JSA_df.sort_values("works_count",ascending=True)["author"].values)[:8]
# by mean JS
scp_authors_most_JS = list(JSA_df.sort_values("mean_jaccard_sim",ascending=False)["author"].values)[:8]
scp_authors_least_JS = list(JSA_df.sort_values("mean_jaccard_sim",ascending=True)["author"].values)[:8]

author_chunks = [scp_authors_most_works,scp_authors_least_works,scp_authors_most_JS,scp_authors_least_JS]

subset_names = ["Most Works","Least Works","Highest Mean JS","Lowest Mean JS"]

for i,x in enumerate(author_chunks):
    plot_df = JS_author_df[JS_author_df["author"].isin(x)]

    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    ax = sns.violinplot(x=plot_df["author"],y=plot_df["sims"])
    ax.set_title(f"Authors by Jaccard Similarity *{subset_names[i]}*")

The distribution of similarity scores within an author's own works shows different behaviors. Some are tight around the middle of similarity scores and dont stray too far up and down. This may be authors writing individual articles outside of a series but not getting radically experimental. Many have short long tails at higher similarity scores. This may potentially indicate creating short series or otherwise a few related articles. Tails to the bottom likely indicate the author going highly experimental with the format or at least far outside their standard style. Ralliston, the author with the highest mean similarity score, is quite elongated with many articles highly similar to each other. However, it still has a tail at the very low end, potentially indicating an attempt to stray from their standard format. Roundhouse looks bimodal, which might be an indication of experiment after writing in a more standard format or visa-versa.

Note on anomaly detection from previous runs.¶

This method identified a few anomalies in the data the first time it was run. Disappointedly, many of the articles with lots of references were simply due to authors page information getting left in the main text. Identified, I parsed those out to remove authors just listing their other articles from subsequent runs.

No surprise that some of the most connected articles are also the most popular articles. 682 at the top is the hard to destroy reptile. SCP-682 is basically invincible as it will always adapt to whatever damage. As such, writers tend to put it up against other powerful SCPs and it functions as the immovable object in these unstoppable force vs immovable object scenarios. 500 is a panacea that cures all disease. Similar placed in testing logs against SCPs that are infectious. A lot are based on testing logs.

Other Methods Attempeted¶

I will just note that I did quite a bit of work on clustering methods using TD-IDF and dimensionality reduction. However, this did not yield meaningful results at this stage as the clustering methods on text data did not meaningfully separate the texts. What little could be drawn from it was better done with the similarity searching. I suspect that incorporating neural network embeddings and deep learning though that is beyond the scope of this class to incorporate. The code is not currently useful, in a separate notebook, and cluttered. Therefore, Ill leave it out to not fill the report with messy code.

I also did some supervised learning and simple text generation. However, that is not related to the topics of this class so also parsed out.

Conclusions and Improvements Future Work¶

  • After trying various methods of data analysis on this set, similarity searching has proven to be most effective. This is not too surprising as it is a method used in class that was designed for text data analysis. Similarity search methods have shown to be quite effective for this task. It would be good to attempt similarity search using more advanced metrics. Though more advanced similarity search methods I found were too slow to go through the database in a reasonable amount of time. Would have to be particularly strict about subsetting articles combinations to investigate.

  • Social network analysis was an outside the box experimentation of its normal use. It definitely produced some useful results but its not as principled of an application and would need to experiment more.

  • TD-IDF was used for both clustering and dimensionality reduction, similar to what was done in class. It would be good to try with more advanced trained neural network embeddings. Though training embeddings takes some time and outside the techniques of this class. An autoencoder may be promising, as it is semi-supervised (requiring no labels), and would be a combination of both custom embedding creation and custom dimensionality reduction in one model.

  • The dataset was a bit more limited and inconsistent than I would have liked it to be. A lot of time was needed for specialized cleaning and feature extraction from inconsistent formats and a lot of data was missing. Building a better web scraper to update and collect missing information would be useful for improvements. However, it would be good to deploy these methods on a larger dataset of short story writing from another source.

  • Id be curious to attempt market basket style analysis using a word bag from documents as kind of a basket. Then it should be possible to evaluate a word appearing if another word appeared and similar evaluations. I did not attempt this acknowledging that this set is too small with potentially very long texts for this to feasibly work. Its an unusual idea but on a larger set of documents with less text per document something like this may work.
